00275 //{
00276     // In regards to whether to '_ = model.TokenWalker.Consume();'
00277     // at the start of the while loop, or at the end:
00278     //
00279     // The end is better because:
00280     // 
00281     // - Anytime one wants to check the previous token,
00282     // with the 'Consume()' at the end of the loop then one can use 'model.TokenWalker.Previous'.
00283     // But, if 'Consume()' is at the start of the loop then one has to use 'model.TokenWalker.Peek(-2)' and that feels very janky.
00284     // 
00285     // - As well, helps ensure a "handle-syntax" does not 'Consume()' someone elses syntax.
00286     // If an individual "syntax" cannot make sense of the current token,
00287     // then it can just return to the main loop and the main loop will deal with it.
00288     //
00289     // On a different note:
00290     //
00291     // 'should return to the main loop'
00292     // - The end of every statement
00293     // - The start of a code block
00294     // - The end of a code block
00295     //
00296     // The goal with every iteration of the main loop,
00297     // is to narrow down the possible syntax that is occuring.
00298     // Then to invoke some other method that will handle that syntax
00299     // entirely, and then return to the main loop for the next syntax to start being parsed.
00300     //
00301     // For example, multiple consecutive keywords might be an ambiguous syntax.
00302     // Therefore, the main loop should push these keywords onto the 'StatementStack'.
00303     // Then, eventually a disambiguating token will be encountered.
00304     // At this point, the corresponding method to handle the syntax can be invoked,
00305     // and the method can pop off the 'StatementStack' to see the "related" tokens.
00306     //
00307     // There are two loops:
00308     // - Statement Loop
00309     // - Expression Loop
00310     //
00311     // Statement loop exists in CSharpParser.cs (this file).
00312     // Expression loop exists in ParseOthers.cs (a relative path from this file: './Internals/ParseOthers.cs').
00313     //
00314     // The parser should gracefully handle syntax that does not compile.
00315     // i.e.: if a syntactical error can be recovered from, then
00316     // the parser is expected to recover.
00317     //
00318     // For example, "(;"
00319     // For the sake of the example, this is presumed to start a ParenthesizedExpressionNode.
00320     // It goes on to see a StatementDelimiterToken before it sees a CloseParenthesisToken.
00321     // Instead of cascading syntactical errors to the text that comes after this (imagine this is part of a source code file)
00322     // the ParenthesizedExpressionNode should report a diagnostic error,
00323     // but then return back to the main loop.
00324     // The main loop will see a StatementDelimiterToken, and then a new statement will begin
00325     // as if nothing went wrong. This allows the rest of the text file to parse with the "same result".
00326     // 
00327     // The parsing is at times done 'breadth first'.
00328     // Because, a class definition might be:
00329     //
00330     // ````public class MyClass
00331     // ````{
00332     // ```` public MyClass(string firstName)
00333     // ````    {
00334     // ````     FirstName = firstName;
00335     // ```` }
00336     // ````
00337     // ```` public string FirstName { get; set; }
00338     // ````}
00339     //
00340     // In this scenario the 'FirstName' property is being referenced from within the class's constructor.
00341     // Yet, the constructor is defined above the property it references.
00342     //
00343     // Instead of parsing 'depth first', in this scenario the index of the token that
00344     // starts the code block body of the constructor definition is remembered,
00345     // then the parser skips until it finds the matching close brace
00346     // (by counting the open brace and close braces until it evens out).
00347     //
00348     // Once the class definition is finished being parsed, then the deferred parsing will start.
00349     // This will modify the 'TokenWalker' such that it now is pointing at the previously "remembered"
00350     // token that starts the code block of the constructor definition.
00351     //
00352     // As well, the 'TokenWalker' is told what index to return to once finished parsing the child scope.
00353     // In this case the 'TokenWalker' would return to the index that represents the 'CloseBraceToken'
00354     // of the class definition.
00355     // 
00356     // If there were many child scopes that needed to be 'defer parsed' then the same
00357     // code will be hit as was initially, and each time a child scope is 'defer parsed'
00358     // it is removed from the list of child scopes that need to be 'defer parsed'.
00359     //
00360     // Regarding StatementDelimiterToken, OpenBraceToken, and CloseBraceToken:
00361     // - These syntax hold a greater meaning than the "individual syntax".
00362     // For example: "1;".
00363     // In the example '1' is a NumericLiteralToken.
00364     // Furthermore, a NumericLiteralToken can be parsed as a 'LiteralExpressionNode'.
00365     // But, the ending StatementDelimiterToken does not belong to the 'LiteralExpressionNode'.
00366     // It is to be "provided" to the main statement loop, to be processed there.
00367     // 
00368     // In short, syntax shouldn't consume tokens that don't belong to them.
00369     // And it is being stated that 'StatementDelimiterToken, OpenBraceToken, and CloseBraceToken'
00370     // in general do not belong to a syntax.
00371     //
00372     // Some exceptions to this would be a property definition "public string FirstName { get; set; }".
00373     // Here, the OpenBraceToken and CloseBraceToken are not being used in the same sense
00374     // as they are when defining scope.
00375     // 
00376     // So, the property definition should consume those OpenBraceToken and CloseBraceToken.
00377     //
00378     // However, consider this example:
00379     //
00380     // ````public string FirstName
00381     // ````{
00382     // ```` get
00383     // ```` {
00384     // ````     return _firstName;
00385     // ```` }
00386     // ```` set => _firstName = value;
00387     // ````}
00388     //
00389     // Here, the property's "getter" is defining a code block.
00390     // So, the brace tokens that deliminate the "getter", ought to
00391     // "visit" the main loop for a moment. Then it can continue on with the property syntax.
00392 //}
